With autonomous vehicles fully deployed, we will need MUCH fewer cars than we do today, which in turn will hurt car companies and make the companies providing the autonomous software like $GOOG get super rich.

But my opinion is, that makes Ford a good investment for the long term. Do DD and GL!

Title: Lach14
st_3SL2gug:
Much has been said about the 'great rotation' of momentum into value stocks in the past few days.  Indeed, in the last two weeks, the Russell 2000 small cap index has seen the largest monthly inflows  since 2016, sending the index up 6.5% in the latest week.  Meanwhile, momentum stocks, as evidenced by the $MTUM momentum etf, fell 2.5%.

While some see that as a rotation, others see it as a sign of strong stock market strength, as small caps are 'catching up' to momentum leaders.

So Russell's rise is not necessarily due to selling the growth stocks, (altho they are being sold) but rather a broadening out of breadth, as the advance decline line for SP500 hits new highs.  

The percent of stocks above their 50 DMA on the SP500 went from 28% in August to 71% as of 9/13/19, indicating most stocks are participating in the rally.  

Nasdaq's percent of stocks above their 50 DMA went from 25% in August to 65% as of Friday.  Similarly bullish for the tech stocks.

$AAPL 5G isn’t there yet 

Right now, there’s no such thing as a 5G phone that supports all the 5G bands and technologies that carriers and device makers ultimately want. Qualcomm is still on its first-generation 5G modem, and companies like Samsung are making headway of their own.

But a multirung strategy that factors in low-, mid-, and high-band spectrum is crucial to making 5G connectivity feel whole, and none of the devices on the market currently will be able to meet that vision when the carriers pursuing it are ready. By next September, Qualcomm will almost certainly have introduced a more capable and future-proofed 5G modem that will better unlock all the potential we keep hearing about.
